//! Pure 1907 Lapicque Integrate-and-Fire neuron model, which is the biological root of all spiking neuron models.
//! This is the simplest possible spiking neuron model, and serves as a baseline for more complex models like Izhikevich and Hodgkin-Huxley.
//! It captures the essential "integrate and fire" behavior of neurons, where the membrane potential integrates incoming stimuli and fires a spike when a threshold is reached, followed by a reset. 
//! This model is computationally efficient and can be used for large-scale simulations where biological realism is less critical, or as a building block for more complex models.|
//! It is also a useful educational tool for understanding the fundamental principles of spiking neuron dynamics and synaptic plasticity. 
//! The LIF model is often used in neuromorphic hardware implementations due to its simplicity and efficiency, making it a key component in the development of energy-efficient spiking neural networks for applications like pattern recognition, sensory processing, and reinforcement learning.
//!  In the context of this crate, the LIF neuron serves as a fast, reactive component that can be used in conjunction with more complex Izhikevich neurons and reward-modulated STDP learning rules to create a versatile and biologically-inspired spiking neural network engine.
//! The LIF model is defined by a simple differential equation that describes how the membrane potential changes over time in response to incoming stimuli and passive decay. When the membrane potential reaches a certain threshold, the neuron fires a spike and resets its potential, simulating the refractory period observed in biological neurons.
//! Reference: Lapicque, L. (1907). Recherches quantitatives sur l'excitation électrique des nerfs traitée comme une polarisation. Journal de Physiologie et de Pathologie Générale, 9, 620–635.
//! Note: The original codebase had a more complex neuron model with plasticity, but this LIF implementation is a simplified version that focuses on the core integrate-and-fire dynamics without the additional complexity of the original model.
//! The weights and plasticity mechanisms will be handled separately in the reward-modulated  STDP module, allowing us to keep the LIF neuron model clean and focused on its core functionality. This separation of concerns also makes it easier to modify or extend the neuron model in the future without affecting the learning rules, and vice versa. 
//! The LIF neuron can be used as a building block in larger networks where different types of neurons (e.g., Izhikevich) can be combined to create a rich diversity of firing patterns and computational capabilities, while still maintaining the simplicity and efficiency of the LIF model for certain parts of the network that require fast, reactive behavior.
//! The LIF model is also a useful tool for studying the effects of synaptic inputs and neuromodulators on neuronal firing patterns, as it allows us to easily manipulate the membrane potential and threshold dynamics in response to different stimuli and modulatory signals, providing insights into how neurons process information and adapt their behavior in response to changing conditions.
//! The LIF neuron can also be used in conjunction with the reward-modulated STDP learning rules to create a simple yet powerful learning system that can adapt its synaptic weights based on the timing of pre- and post-synaptic spikes and the presence of reward signals, allowing us to explore the principles of reinforcement learning and synaptic plasticity in a biologically-inspired context.
//! The LIF model is a fundamental component of many neuromorphic computing systems and spiking neural network simulations, and serves as a key building block for understanding the dynamics of spiking neurons and their role in information processing and learning in the brain.
//!  By implementing the LIF neuron model in this crate, we provide a simple and efficient tool for simulating spiking neural networks and exploring the principles of neuronal dynamics and synaptic plasticity in a biologically-inspired context, while also laying the groundwork for more complex models and learning rules that can be built on top of this foundational neuron model.
//! The LIF neuron model is defined by the following equations:
//! dv/dt = -(v - v_rest) / tau + I(t) / C 
//! Where v is the membrane potential, v_rest is the resting potential, tau is the membrane time constant, I(t) is the input current, and C is the membrane capacitance. When v reaches a threshold value (v_threshold), the neuron fires a spike and resets its potential to a reset value (v_reset), simulating the refractory period observed in biological neurons.   
